**INTRODUCTION**

A chatbot is a computer application that can mimic a human-like conversation in natural language. The concept of chatbot has evolved so much since its inception in 1960s.Chatbots have transformed into an intelligent conversational agents from just an interface to communicate with the users.

**2.1 HOW CHATBOTS WORK**

Today chatbots are integrated into systems that provide users with entertainment, learning experience, information retrieval and online support. In the present scenario, chatbots are perceived as an interface that can greatly facilitate in information retrieval through Human Computer Interaction(HCI) since the chatbot application can reduce many levels of the program flow by interacting with an user to fetch the exact results, an user wants from the system. For example, consider a pizza delivery website that takes orders from customers using a chatbot interface integrated into their application. Suppose,a customer visiting the website to place order that comprises a large pizza with extra cheese and a pepsi, he has to type in the details of the order in the chatbot interface. A typical conversation with the chatbot could be like this:

Bot : &quot;Welcome. How can I help you? &quot;

Customer : &quot;I would like to place an order&quot;

Bot : &quot;Okay sure , when you are ready&quot;

Customer : &quot;Get me a large pizza with extra cheese&quot;

Bot : &quot;Done. Can I get anything else for you. Would you like a pepsi along with this, most people prefer this combo&quot;

Customer : &quot;Ok then, add a pepsi too&quot;

Bot : &quot;Thank you sir/mam.Your order is placed. Please pay Rs.486 in payment page you will be redirected now.&quot;

As you can see the usual path an user follows to place an order is greatly simplified by using the chatbot interface in the place. This reduction in the usual program flow attributes to the importance and the gaining popularity of the chatbot in recent times.



**2.2 HOW TO DEVELOP A CHATBOT**

A typical chatbot application consists of an interface for input and output, a core machine learning model (may include AI), storage adapter. When Building AI and ML for your Chatbot, you basically have two main options at this time.You can use a third party tool which will take care of the AI/Conversational part of the Chabot or you can make your own using Machine Learning. The second options sounds overwhelming, but quite a few developers are choosing to go this route and many companies are trying to democratize Machine Learning.

**Machine learning approach**

You can build your own NLP/NLU by using Machine Learning. One of the first things to consider will be the type of model you want to build.-Retrieval Based Model or a Generative Model.

Retrieval-based models are easy to understand and work on. They usually work with a source of predefined and available responses and eventually get and a good command over context and content. The retrieval-based models contain some good configuration of Machine Learning but they are not configured to generate any new text, they just pick the appropriate text from a predefined class and set of texts and project the one that matches the intent of a question or a statement. Retrieval based models will go perfect will those chatbots that just perform a task and nothing else. You will have a set of answers and your chatbot will answer to user according to them and the keywords

Generative models are hard to understand and setup they do not rely on the predefined class and generate text of their own according to the understandings of a giving question or statement. Generative models work with Machine Translation and translate the content and context to the machine. They generate brand new responses from the scratch and put them in front of the user. If you want to go big, this model is for you. It can be a direct jump in the AI playground but it will make mistakes so you should prepare yourself for them. You will have a feel that you are talking to a human.

**Using an NLP/NLU Platforms**

 Natural Language Processing (NLP) and Natural Language Understanding (NLU) platforms attempt to solve the problem by parsing language into entities, intents and a few other categories. Different NLP platforms may have different names however the essence is more so the same. Here are categories:

**Agents** correspond to applications. Once you train and test an agent, you can integrate it with your app or device.

**Entities** : represent concepts that are often specific to a domain as a way of mapping natural language phrases to canonical phrases that capture their meaning.

**Intents** represent a mapping between what a user says and what action should be taken by your software.

**Actions** correspond to the steps your application will take when specific intents are triggered by user inputs. An action may have parameters for specifying detailed information about it.

**Contexts** are strings that represent the current context of the user expression. This is useful for differentiating phrases which might be vague and have different meaning depending on what was spoken previously.

Examples of such platforms are IBM&#39;s Watson, Facebook&#39;s &#39;Bot for messenger&#39;,wix.ai, Pandorabots etc.

**2.3 API CENTRIC CHATBOT**

In this work, we emphasized to build a chatbot platform that is capable of machine learning and natural language processing using python&#39;s Chatterbot library and NLTK â€“ Natural Language ToolKit. The core model of ML used is Retrieval based model. The platform is language independent, can be easily trained and integrated with other applications.

**ChatterBot** is a Python library that makes it easy to generate automated responses to a user&#39;s input. ChatterBot uses a selection of machine learning algorithms to produce different types of responses. This makes it easy for developers to create chat bots and automate conversations with users. NLTK is a leading platform for building Python programs to work with human language data. It provides easy-to-use interfaces to [over 50 corpora and lexical resources](http://nltk.org/nltk_data/) such as WordNet, along with a suite of text processing libraries for classification, tokenization, stemming, and tagging, parsing, and semantic reasoning, wrappers for industrial-strength NLP libraries.

An API-Centric or API-Driven Web Application is a web application that basically executes most, if not, all its functionality through API calls. In an API-Centric web application, front-end communicates with backend using just APIs.There are a number of advantages of developing an API-centric [web application](http://www.wavemaker.com/benefits/), namely,

1. Easy consumption on multiple devices. RESTful APIs provide a lightweight integration model that significantly helps in creating mobile applications.
2. Business logic is well contained with individual APIs.
3. Ease of application development as focus of application in on the front end user interaction.
4. Forces Reuse, as APIs developed can be used by multiple application on multiple form factors.

This project uses Django REST framework to develop RESTful APIs which can be used to hook the frontend of applications with the chatbot platform to use the features of the platform typically get an output statement for an input statement.

**3.2 TRAINING**

The vast majority of production systems today are retrieval-based, or a combination of retrieval-based and generative. Google&#39;s [Smart Reply](http://arxiv.org/abs/1606.04870) is a good example. Generative models are an active area of research, but we&#39;re not quite there yet. If you want to build a conversational agent today your best bet is most likely a retrieval-based model. A retrieval based model needs some amount of data to start with so that it can return expected results by retrieving the known data that satisfies some rules. The process of adding predefined datasets to implement a retrieval based model is called **Training**.

ChatterBot includes tools that help simplify the process of training a chatbot instance. ChatterBot&#39;s training process involves loading example dialog into the chat bot&#39;s database. This either creates or builds upon the graph data structure that represents the sets of known statements and responses. Figure 3.1 represents the knowledge graph stored in database. When a chat bot trainer is provided with a data set, it creates the necessary entries in the chat bot&#39;s knowledge graph so that the statement inputs and responses are correctly represented. An [untrained instance](https://chatterbot.readthedocs.io/en/stable/index.html#term-untrained-instance) of ChatterBot starts off with no knowledge of how to communicate. Each time an user enters a [statement](https://chatterbot.readthedocs.io/en/stable/index.html#term-statement), the library saves the text that they entered and the text that the statement was in response to. As ChatterBot receives more input the number of responses that it can reply and the accuracy of each response in relation to the input statement increase.

**LOGICAL ADAPTERS**

After choosing a machine learning model, it is necessary to define rules that govern the logic of the model chosen. This is where the logical adapter comes into picture.In simple terms, the logical adapter is the set of all algorithms and methods that determines how a chatbot selects a response to a given input statement.

**4.1 HOW IT WORKS**

The program usually selects the closest matching [response](https://chatterbot.readthedocs.io/en/stable/index.html#term-response) by searching for the closest matching known statement that matches the input, it then chooses a response from the selection of known responses to that statement.Each response returned has a confidence value associated with it. Confidence value is the measure of precision of the output statement for a given input statement. Figure 4.1 depicts the program flow in the chatbot application developed.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



Consider each logical adapters as a black-box which takes an statement as input and returns two values-an output statement and a confidence value associated with the output statement. Internally within the box complex comparison and response selection algorithms are invoked. These NLP(Natural Language Processing) algorithms use NLTK  to import predefined library functions.

**4.2**** BEST MATCH ADAPTER**

The logic adapter that your bot uses can be specified by setting the logic\_adapters parameter to the import path of the logic adapter you want to use.It is possible to enter any number of logic adapters for your bot to use. If multiple adapters are used, then the bot will return the response with the highest calculated confidence value. If multiple adapters return the same confidence, then the adapter that is entered into the list first will take priority.

The BestMatch logic adapter selects a response based on the best know match to a given statement. The best match adapter determines uses an function to compare the input statement to known statements. Once it finds the closest match to the input statement, it uses another function to select one of the known responses to that statement.

**Statements**

ChatterBot&#39;s statement objects represent either an input statement that the chat bot has received from a user, or an output statement that the chat bot has returned based on some input. ChatterBot stores knowledge of conversations as statements. Each statement can have any number possible responses. Figure 4.2 depicts the structure of Statement model.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



Each Statement object has an in\_response\_to reference which links the statement to a number of other statements that it has been learned to be in response to. The in\_response\_to attribute is essentially a reference to all parent statements of the current statement.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



The Response object&#39;s occurrence attribute indicates the number of times that the statement has been given as a response. This makes it possible for the chat bot to determine if a particular response is more commonly used than another. Figure 4.3 shows this.

**Comparison function**

ChatterBot uses Statement objects to hold information about things that can be said. An important part of how a chat bot selects a response is based on its ability to compare two statements to each other. There is a number of ways to do this, and ChatterBot comes with a handful of method built in for you to use. This module contains various text-comparison algorithms designed to compare one statement to another. Figure 4.4 shows how to define a coparison function in chatterbot.

**Jaccard similarity**

Calculates the similarity of two statements based on the Jaccard index.The Jaccard index is composed of a numerator and denominator. In the numerator, we count the number of items that are shared between the sets. In the denominator, we count the total number of items across both sets. Let&#39;s say we define sentences to be equivalent if 50% or more of their tokens are equivalent. Here are two sample sentences:

The young cat is hungry. The cat is very hungry.

When we parse these sentences to remove stopwords, we end up with the following two sets:

{young, cat, hungry} {cat, very, hungry}

In our example above, our intersection is {cat, hungry}, which has count of two. The union of the sets is {young, cat, very, hungry}, which has a count of four. Therefore, our [Jaccard similarity index](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jaccard_index) is two divided by four, or 50%. Given our threshold above, we would consider this to be a match.

**Levenstein Distance**

Compare two statements based on the Levenstein distance of each statement&#39;s text.

For example, there is a 65% similarity between the statements &quot;where is the post office?&quot; and &quot;looking for the post office&quot; based on the Levenstein distance algorithm.

| Returns: | The percent of similarity between the text of the statements |

**Sentiment Comparison**

Calculate the similarity of two statements based on the closeness of the sentiment value calculated for each statement.

**Synset Distance:**

Calculate the similarity of two statements. This is based on the total maximum synset similarity between each word in each sentence.

This algorithm uses the [wordnet](http://www.nltk.org/howto/wordnet.html) functionality of [NLTK](http://www.nltk.org/) to determine the similarity of two statements based on the path similarity between each token of each statement. This is essentially an evaluation of the closeness of synonyms.

**4.3 CUSTOM LOGICAL ADAPTER**

As discussed above, there are numerous ways in which comparison function can be implemented. One of the most reliable and popular algorithm is **Levenstein Distenace.** Levenshtein distance (LD) is a measure of the similarity between two strings, which we will refer to as the source string (s) and the target string (t). The distance is the number of deletions, insertions, or substitutions required to transform s into t. For example,

- If s is &quot;test&quot; and t is &quot;test&quot;, then LD(s,t) = 0, because no transformations are needed. The strings are already identical.
- If s is &quot;test&quot; and t is &quot;tent&quot;, then LD(s,t) = 1, because one substitution (change &quot;s&quot; to &quot;n&quot;) is sufficient to transform s into t.

The same algorithm is used for many other real time applications as well like spell checking, DNA analysis, even plagiarism detection that will be used to verify the genuineness of this thesis may use this algorithm. In this project, initially the comparison function was implemented using Chatterbot&#39;s in-built method that implemented levenstein distance from NLTK library.The algorithm works as follows:

1. Get an input statement.

2. Compare the input statement with responses stored in the database. Calculate the levenstein distance for the pairs.

3. Repeat step 2 for all responses.

4. Return the response with lowest levenstein distance. In case of tie, return the one that was calculated first.

This implementation worked just fine for small database with small amount of data stored but as the database scaled, the performance of the algorithm was getting poorer. So there was a need to modify the algorithm for large datasets.Bitap algorithm with modifications by Wu and Manber which is an approximate string matching algorithm was then considered and it scored well for large databases. The algorithm is same as pure levenstein algorithm with a slight modification in its implementation. Figure 3.5 shows the difference in performance between two algorithms. The algorithm works as follows:

1. Get input statement and a value k.

2. Compare the input statement with responses stored in the database. Calculate the levenstein distance (LD) for the pair. If LD &lt;= k , return the response as output statement.

3. Repeat step 2 for all responses.

4. In case, no response has crossed the threshold k, return the response with lowest levenstein distance. In case of tie, return the one that was calculated first.

Since, the number of comparisons are drastically reduced in the Bitap algorithm while still returning a precise response to some degree, it is preferred for this project obviously. The precision of the response statement for a given input statement and performance depend on the value of k. The lower the value of k,the more precise is the output and lower performance. This makes the algorithm flexible for implementation. Consider there are n statements to be compared with the input statement of size k. If the average size of n statements is p then the Levenstein algorithm returns the result in O(nkp) + O(n) whereas the modified algorithm returns in O(nkp) in worst case and O(nkj) in an average case where j &lt; p.

**4.4 MULTIPLE LOGIC ADAPTERS**

ChatterBot internally uses a special logic adapter that allows it to choose the best response generated by any number of other logic adapters.

## Selecting a response from multiple logic adapters

The MultiLogicAdapter is used to select a single response from the responses returned by all of the logic adapters that the chat bot has been configured to use. Each response returned by the logic adapters includes a confidence score that indicates the likeliness that the returned statement is a valid response to the input.

### **Response selection**

The MultiLogicAdapter will return the response statement that has the greatest confidence score. The only exception to this is a case where multiple logic adapters return the same statement and therefore _agree_ on that response.

For this example, consider a scenario where multiple logic adapters are being used. Assume the following results in Table 3.1 were returned by a chat bot&#39;s logic adapters.

| **Confidence** | **Statement** |
| --- | --- |
| 0.2 | Good morning |
| 0.5 | Good morning |
| 0.7 | Good night |

In this case, two of the logic adapters have generated the same result. When multiple logic adapters come to to the same conclusion, that statement is given priority over another response with a possibly higher confidence score. The fact that the multiple adapters agreed on a response is a significant indicator that a particular statement has a greater probability of being a more accurate response to the input.

When multiple adapters agree on a response, the greatest confidence score that was generated for that response will be returned with it.

## Methods

**5.1 STORAGE INTERFACE**

Storage interface allows Chatterbot to connect to different storage backends. Chatterbot provides storage APIs to connect to MongoDB, MySQL, and Json file storage. The storage adapter that your bot uses can be specified by setting the storage\_adapter parameter to the import path of the storage adapter you want to use. Figure 5.1 shows how to declare storage adapter in chatterbot.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



Json file storage is easier to implement and retrieve information for a small development database.But for a large production database that scales invariably, it is not suitable for this project.Also there is no security for the flat files stored.For this project, MongoDB is chosen over MySQL because MongoDB uses dynamic schemas, meaning that you can create records without first defining the structure, such as the fields or the types of their values. You can change the structure of records (which we call documents) simply by adding new fields or deleting existing ones. This data model give you the ability to represent hierarchical relationships, to store arrays, and other more complex structures easily. Documents in a collection need not have an identical set of fields and denormalization of data is common. MongoDB was also designed with high availability and scalability in mind, and includes out-of-the-box replication and auto-shading. Table 5.1 shows comparison between MySQL and MongoDB.

**5.2 MODELS:**

There are three models that are used to define a conversation in the chatbot.

**Statement**

**       ** This model stores all the text that are input and output to the chatbot.It consists of three fields:

1. Id â€“ unique id of a field
2. text - string that represents a statement.
3. created at - latest time of getting this string
4. extra data â€“ confidence score associated with this string when it is returned as output statement of a given input statement.

**       **  **Response**

This model stores all the text that are returned as responses for different input statements in the chatbot.It consists of two fields:

1. Id - unique id of a field.
2. response â€“ string that was returned as a response to the statement represented by statement\_id.
3. Statement\_id â€“ id of the input statement for which this response string was returned.
4. Occurrence â€“ an integer field that represents number of times this particular response was returned for different input strings.This particular variable is used in filters.

**6.2 DJANGO REST FRAMEWORK**

The APIs for the platform is developed using Django REST framework. Django REST framework is a powerful and flexible toolkit for building Web APIs. DRF also supports serialization of both ORM and non-ORM data sources. DRF is so similar to Django but it has got some extensive additional features to support development of APIs. To understand DRF better, one needs to know the directory structure of a DRF project. There are three main files: urls.py, views.py, settings.py.

**urls.py**

This file contains all the legitimate routes that could be requested from the application. The corresponding routes are internally mapped to different views that the browser will be returning.

**views.py**

This file contains all the frontend views that is returned when its corresponding routes is requested. Views.py can contain methods that implement a functionality and returns a result. These methods can be mapped to different HTTP requests such as GET, POST, PUT ,DELETE etc. and results for different requests could be made distinct- a concept called CRUD.

**settings.py**

This file contains all the necessary settings that are required for the project to work properly.All the default configurations and database adapters are defined here.

A typical implementation of API is as follows:

1. An API request pointing to any of the routes defined in urls.py.

2. The corresponding view that is mapped the matched URL is executed. If the view file contains a method that matches the type of HTTP request, then it is invoked.

3.  If the request is a POST request, Json serializer serializes the input object into Json format and transfers it to the modules that the method invokes.

4. The processed result is again de-serialized and sent back to the view (frontend at user end).

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In this project, if a third party application issues the API request, in this case, an input statement sent from an interface of an application, the API request is directed to a view which serializes the input statement into JSON data and sends it to a method that invokes the logical adapter and sends the deserialized JSON data. The output statement is again serialized at the view and sent to user&#39;s view where it is de-serialized to present to the users. Figure 6.2 shows an example API end point in urls.py.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)



The module for training comes with manage.py in-built with chatterbot. This module adds the training data into the database when executed as python module in terminal. Figure 6.4 shows the training module being executed

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

**OPEN SOURCE PROJECT**

** **

Generally, open source refers to a [computer program](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_program) in which the [source code](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Source_code) is available to the general public for use or modification from its original design. Open-source code is meant to be a collaborative effort, where programmers improve upon the source code and share the changes within the community. Code is released under the terms of a [software license](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_license). Depending on the license terms, others may then download, modify, and publish their version (fork) back to the community. Advantage of making a project open source is that the project gets better with many developers contributing to the optimization, bug fixes in the source code. So this project is available as open source project in Github for other developers to refer to.



**7.1 HOW TO USE THE PLATFORM**

All information about how to use the platform is available in Github at [https://github.com/Surendhar95/ChatBot](https://github.com/Surendhar95/ChatBot). The platform is hosted at Heroku cloud for now. The production domain may change in future but the documentation available at Github will be updated instantly in the event of any change.



**7.2 DOCUMENTATION**

Detailed documentation on how to use the platform, configure the platform to specific needs, training, API references are available as README file in Github at [https://github.com/Surendhar95/ChatBot](https://github.com/Surendhar95/ChatBot).



**7.3 HOW TO CONTRIBUTE**

In order to contribute to the project, the user must be familiar with git and Github. If the user is familiar with them, he/she can fork the project, work on the project and issue pull request if some bug or scope for improvisation is found in the project. The project is available as a public repository which means it can be downloaded also. Any contribution to the project is always welcome.

## CHAPTER-8

**SUMMARY AND CONCLUSION**



**8.1 SUMMARY**

A chatbot platform that can learn as user interacts with it is built. And it offers huge flexibility in training, integration and configuration. The platform is capable of returning logical responses for different input statement. Since the whole backend is readily available as chatbot platform, integration with any frontend application becomes much easier with the out of the box APIs and documentation to learn. Developers can easily avail the features of the platform using simple RESTful APIs developed as part of the platform. The whole platform was built with python&#39;s chatterbot library ,NLTK and MongoDB interface. Django REST framework is used to integrate all the python modules developed using above tools to offer a end point to connect with the platform.



**8.2 CONCLUSION**

Since an out of box platform is available to be used, many online business websites which may require a chatbot to be integrated in its application can do so easily, if they choose to use this platform. This platform cannot be compared with enterprise NLP/AI platforms like IBM&#39;s Watson, PandoraBots rather it is an attempt to prove that if you find something amusing in an idea, you may as well build it to know it better. But the project provides a massive scope to become as a popular platform in future with many developers stepping in to pitch their ideas in open source community.

**8.3**  **directionS for future work**

The scope of this idea is huge. There are lot of areas that are yet to be explored to make this project a better one in future. Some of the improvisation that can be done in this project are:

1. To try to implement the Generative model in the place of Retrieval model. Since Generative model for a generic project like this in nearly impossible, a specific domain can be explored to bring in that change in the project.
2. Developing a website that can describe about this project better to the open world.
3. Rope in more developers into the project who are interested in pitching some help to make it better.
